data.content:
Your code **doesn't use `Thread.Abort`**, so there's no `PlatformNotSupportedException` risk. However, it has two issues worth addressing during migration:

### 1. Closure bug over `item`
The `foreach` variable is captured by reference — all threads may process the **last item**. (.NET Framework foreach had this bug; C# 5+ fixed it for `foreach`, but it's still a code-smell pattern.)

### 2. Modern replacement
Manual `Thread` management should be replaced with `Task` or `Parallel.ForEach` in .NET 8:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        Parallel.ForEach(items, item =>
        {
            Process(item);
        });
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        // simulate work — use Task.Delay if going async
        Thread.Sleep(100);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

### Thread.Abort migration cheat sheet (for when you do encounter it):

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 replacement |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationToken` + cooperative cancellation |
| `Thread.Sleep()` | `await Task.Delay()` (async) or keep for sync |
| `new Thread(...)` | `Task.Run(...)` or `Parallel.ForEach` |
| `Thread.Join()` | `await Task.WhenAll(...)` |

`Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 5+. The canonical fix is passing a `CancellationToken` and checking `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at safe points instead of relying on `ThreadAbortException`.
